{
  "answer": "In Iqbal's \"Husn o Ishq,\" the central claim is that Beauty (*husn*) and Love (*ishq*) form a singular, interdependent metaphysical unity in which each drives the perfection of the other: Beauty spurs Love toward its fulfillment, while Love manifests Beauty's essence.[^1][^2]\n\nA stark counter-claim in Ghalib's *Diwan* appears in ghazal 228, where the tyrants' beauty (*husn-e-jabron*) deranges the lover's soul, portraying beauty as a cruel, unhinging force amid love's torment.[^3] Love here demands endurance of the beloved's disdainful sharpness, as in ghazal 222.[^4]\n\nIqbal has not refuted Ghalib's view of love's agony so much as changed the subject, recasting the *husn-ishq* dynamic from existential cruelty and stoic suffering to a constructive, perfecting cosmology aligned with Iqbal's philosophy of self-realization.[^5]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, [Husn o Ishq](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/13-husn-o-ishq/translation/#p-73eab8).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, [Husn o Ishq](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/13-husn-o-ishq/translation/#p-7a49e3).\n\n[^3]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [pa-ba-daaman ho raha hoon baske main sahra-navard](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/228-pa-ba-daaman-ho-raha-hoon-baske-main-sahra-navard/translation/#p-7370e8).\n\n[^4]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [jarahat tohfa, almas armaghan, dagh-e-jigar hadiya](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/222-jarahat-tohfa-almas-armaghan-dagh-e-jigar-hadiya/translation/#p-7e3de9).\n\n[^5]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, [Husn o Ishq](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/13-husn-o-ishq/translation/).",
